"p\",[[0,[],0,\"The 12-year-old Mexican scientist looks skeptical for a moment, then says, exasperated, \\\"I think it might be because there is absolutely no evidence to support the statement that \"],[0,[3],1,\"vaccines are linked to autism\"],[0,[],0,\" in any way whatsoever.\\\" I mean, have you \"],[0,[2],1,\"met\"],[0,[],0,\" a sassier kid? Specifically, a kid who gets sassy about \"],[0,[2],1,\"science\"],[0,[],0,\"? Bill Nye, watch your back.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Not only does Arturo have personality, but he's got the facts down. \\\"Smallpox was eradicated thanks to vaccines!\\\" he says. \\\"And you might think, 'It's my child, it's my choice.' Okay, I agree. It's your choice if you want to expose your child to deadly diseases, but you know, it's not just your child. It's basically \"],[0,[2],1,\"everyone else's child\"],[0,[],0,\". It's also everyone else's child you're putting in danger because you read some forwarded email.\\\"\"]]],[10,1],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"Sassy, but he's right: vaccines are far more effective than leaving your child unvaccinated, but they're not perfect, either. The mumps vaccine is 88 percent effective, according to \"],[0,[2],1,\"Wired\"],[0,[],0,\", while the vaccines for measles are 97 percent effective. Take, for example, when \"],[0,[4],1,\"parents don't vaccinate their children\"],[0,[],0,\" against measles, which is incredibly easy to spread: by infecting a now-larger, unvaccinated population, measles can more easily reach the vulnerable 3 percent of the vaccinated population whose vaccines weren't effective. According to \"],[0,[2],1,\"Wired\"],[0,[],0,\", once vaccination levels drop below 90 to 95 percent of the population, it can spur outbreaks, since not enough people are vaccinated to keep the disease from spreading.\"]]],[1,\"p\",[[0,[],0,\"\\\"So, please,\\\" Arturo ends his video, before dropping a piece of paper with \\\"mic\\\" written on it. \\\"Vaccinate your children.\\\" It's super shareworthy \u2014 not only to spread the word about vaccination, but to encourage kids to make a difference in STEM, just like Arturo has.\"]]]]}],\"summary\":\"World, meet the next Bill Nye: his name is Marco Arturo, and he's here to school you on the connection between vaccines and autism. It's a contentious topic: The CDC and the World Health Organization both say the causal link is false \u2014 yet vaccine re\",\"primaryMedia\":{\"url\":\"https://typeset-beta.imgix.net/2016/5/2/Screen-Shot-2016-05-31-at-30103-PM-b90f5969-62da-4301-87d6-e7cf461e4de5.png\",\"attribution\":\"Marco Arturo/Facebook\",\"attributionUrl\":\"https://www.facebook.com/224110424640151/videos/224150204636173/?permPage=1\",\"caption\":null},\"author\":{\"id\":1392,\"name\":\"Kenza Moller\",\"twitter\":\"kenzamoller\",\"mediaUrl\":\"https://lovelace-media.imgix.net/uploads/1392/02d753d0-f494-0133-e716-0a315da82319.png\",\"slug\":\"kenza-moller-1392\",\"path\":\"/authors/kenza-moller-1392\"},\"path\":\"/p/this-kid-compiled-all-the-evidence-that-vaccines-cause-autism-its-brilliant-11552\"} })</script> </body> </html> \n"}